The range() function lets you create an iterator so you can loop over some integers. When you use i in range(0, 11), you're essentially asking "will range(0, 11) eventually iterate over i", not "is i within the upper and lower bounds of range(0, 11)". Because range() only works with integers, a float will be iterator over by range, and thus a float will never be in a range.
